Note:
There is no way you can see every single film made, not even from this mysterious canon, and anyone that dismisses you for not having seen film x is an idiot. There shouldn't be any gate keepers, just gate openers (sorry, that was awful but this is twitter).

I have also taught Guardians of the Galaxy for specific narrative reasons and Bukowski to show how poetry can break the rules. These are taught in the context of knowing that they will students will exposed to the literary canon, showing them how they all fit together, in harmon

That's what society always depends on, experts and expertise. That's why I teach Shakespeare, Yeats, Bishop and Plath. I want my students to have an 'in' into what experts see as important and as being at the top of the various art forms. And I (try to) teach them why.

But if you are putting yourself forward as a Western expert then you had better have seen a huge amount of them, and (hopefully) have read widely on the subject.
Each genre has its own canon and I want experts in those genres to have seen the requisite films.

Now, this doesn't mean that if you haven't seen all of these films that you can't talk about films. Of course you can. I don't know everything about Westerns but I can still argue why Fort Apache is one of the best.

What reading Mr Cousins' books and articles, and watching his documentaries, I am being taught that the canon is limited, that it needs to be wider. And, crucially, he points me in the direction of those films that I should seek out.

Daughters of the Dust was cited as an example of a film that can be added to the list.
Added. Not replacing, just expanding.
There are many many more. That is why people like @markcousinsfilm are so important (at least to me).

My view is very simple:
The canon is important.
If you want to call yourself an expert on film you should have seen a good chunk of these films.
But
For me the canon is not a closed list, it is a list that can grow and expand.

So, when we talk about rote learning, about students not thinking for themselves, when we talk about changing the LC, maybe we should talk about alternative ways to get into college.
The points race dominates.

Why?
Because the Leaving Cert leads to college places.
This is a huge issue. Get it wrong for the students and they don't get into college.
That's all we want, to get it right for the students.

We, parents and teachers and thus students, are worried about THE EXAM, the Leaving Cert. This dominates and we don't want to make a mistake and ruin the students' chances of success.
So we fall back on what has been 'right' before and make them learn that.

Again this is partly down to moving from 15 to 18, not wanting to put their head above the parapet.
But we, as teachers, have to look to see how we have contributed to this. And so do parents.

Simply growing up counts for a lot here. They have been, carefully, shown that maybe their answer wasn't the right one, that they can be wrong.
But somewhere they start to be afraid to write down their own thoughts and ideas.

Gaming,
Comics,
TV (indigenous and foreign companies)
Film (as above)
I'm sure that there are others that my narrow experience isn't aware of.

@baloobas1 I think it's just another 'this generation doesn't understand art, they're ruined by social media'. Used to be MTV, before that the television, before that the cinema, before that the radio, before that a different god.....

We don't dismiss our colleagues if they don't like what we like, we shouldn't dismiss our students for the same thing.
(Unless the film they like is Inside I'm Dancing, in that case they should be shunned)

What we shouldn't do is try to 'make' them like a particular poem, play, or film. Hopefully they will but if they don't, that's OK.
Criticising them for not liking what you like is elitist, dismissive and hubristic.

I'm old (according to my children and my students) and I find 2001 and Barry Lyndon boring.
Students can like what they want. As teachers we should be asking them to appreciate the art, the creativity, what is being discussed and how it is being discussed. https://t.co/MUmvCik1MB

I'm not attacking any teacher seconded to @JCforTeachers. I know many of you and I know you all to be professionals dedicated to the betterment of student learning and, indeed, teacher learning.
I'm directing my points at those unwilling to change the specification
The elements that make up the portfolio up to the teacher. Doesn't have to contain an essay. The AT that tests the portfolio can be bluffed. That's the reality.

The reality, on the ground, in the classroom, is that if you put all of these elements together, add in pressure from parents and Principals pushing you to ensure your students achieve a high grade, then something will give. I have heard many teachers say that it is the essay.
How many forms of writing are there? How many purposes are there? Now put the two together and work out the amount of combinations.

The @NCCAie need to be very careful before they mess with a system that, for the most part, works.
The Junior Cycle has been a disaster for my subject, I don't want the Leaving Cert to go the same way
(LC English works pretty well these days, mainly because of how the Qs r worded

I like the idea of continuous assessment but when the result is tied to whether your child gets into the course they want in college this system will be corrupted almost immediately.
(I'd love for students to be able to work on a story for a few months for their LC)

As for inexperienced examiners... 
Dear god. Really? Does anyone want an inexperienced plasterer, doctor, tiler, hairdresser etc doing work for them?

And modules that include 'life skills' of their choice and extracurricular credits? 
Will this be a reward for charitable activities? Will they be able to get credit for coaching the local under 8s?
Or will mummy and daddy get their friends to say that they did the above?

Now think about what will happen with continuous assessment.
Will it be liberate the students? Will the students be able to fully explore their learning?
Or will those with money buy the answers off the Internet? Or maybe write and rewrite their answers with the help of a grind?

Now, let's remind ourselves of the current LC landscape:
Those with the cash get grinds and extra tuition.
Websites sell notes and sample answers.
Those without money don't access the above.
